definition.value: a coating excipient role that is realized by delaying denaturation, disintegration, or some other method of destruction of a drug product including its active ingredients

A protective coating acts against destruction or contamination of a drug preparation by keeping the other drug ingredients, especially active ingredients, away from potentially reactive substances like oxygen, water, and various forms of electromagnetic radiation (e.g., light).

a protective coating excipient role that is realized by a process of delaying release of one or more active ingredients from the drug product until some targeted time or location, typically the small or large intestine, within an organism

An enteric coating also protects the drug preparation from destruction or contamination, but also is designed to disintegrate on a controlled timeline or in a particular place. For instance, some enteric coatings are designed to withstand the relatively low PH of the stomach, but break down in the relatively high PH of the large intestine, allowing an ingredient that would otherwise be destroyed by or absorbed by the stomach to be absorbed in the intestine.

label.value: function-inhibiting glucocorticoid steroid receptor binding disposition

definition.value: A disposition to bind to a glucocorticoid steroid receptor in such a way as to prevent the realization of the function of the receptor.
This is the mechanism of action for all common corticosteroids such as prednisone, hydrocortisone, etc.
A disposition to bind to a beta2-adrenergic receptor in such a way as to activate the realization of the function of the receptor.
This is a mechanism of action for many bronchodilator drugs.
A disposition to bind to a 5-lipoxygenase enzyme in such a way to inhibit the realization of the function of the enzyme.
This is a mechanism of action for many leukotriene modifier drugs.

label.value: non-activating competitive cysteinyl-leukotriene type 1 receptor binding disposition

definition.value: A disposition to bind to a cysteinyl-leukotriene type 1 receptor in such a way to compete with the realization of the function of the receptor.
This is a mechanism of action for many leukotriene modifiers.
A disposition to bind to an alpha1A-adrenergic receptor in such a way to activate the realization of the function of the receptor.
This is a mechanism of action for many sympathomimetic amines.

label.value: non-activating competitive cysteinyl-leukotriene type 1 receptor binding disposition
non-activating competitive muscarinic cholinergic receptors binding disposition

definition.value: A disposition to bind to a muscarinic cholinergic receptor in such a way to compete with the realization of the function of the receptor.
This is a mechanism of action for many anticholinergic bronchodilators.
A disposition to bind to a corticosteroid receptor in such a way as to prevent the realization of the function of the receptor.
This is a mechanism of action for many corticosteroids.
A disposition to bind to a phosphodiesterase receptor in such a way as to compete with the realization of the function of the enzyme.
This is a mechanism of action for many methylxanthines.
A disposition to bind to a interleukin-5 receptor in such a way as to prevent the realization of the function of the receptor.
This is a mechanism of action for many mepolizumab systemics.

label.value: non-activating competitive type III and type IV phosphodiesterase binding disposition

definition.value: A disposition to bind to a type III and type IV phosphodiesterase receptor in such a way as to compete with the realization of the function of the receptor.
This is a mechanism of action for many theophylline systemics.

label.value: non-activating competitive adenosine A1 binding disposition

definition.value: A disposition to bind to an adenosine A1 receptor in such a way as to compete with the realization of the function of the receptor.
This is a mechanism of action for many CNS stimulants.

A dispostion of a molecule to bind a GABA-A receptor in the pocket formed at the junction of the alpha and gamma subunits of the receptor in such a way as to increase the flow of chloride anions through the channel in the receptor, ultimately resulting in enhanced activity of GABA binding to the GABA-A receptor.
This is the mechanism of action of benzodiazepine drugs
A drug product therapeutic function that, if realized, is realized by the regulation of some endocrine process.
